source_code.code:
public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Display display = new Display();
    Shell shell = new Shell(display);
    shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());

    Browser browser = new Browser(shell, SWT.NONE);
    browser.setText("<html><body style='overflow:auto;'>Hello World</body></html>");

    shell.open();
    while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
      if (!display.readAndDispatch()) {
        display.sleep();
      }
    }
  }
}

Bug.WithStack:
Hi,

just FYI, there is a simple way of hiding the Scrollbars from the Browser
widget, in case not required. Just set a style="overflow:auto;" into the <body>
Tag and Scrollbars will only be visible, when required. I have tested this on
Windows, not sure about the results on other OS, but according to SelfHTML, this
CSS is accepted by all Browsers.

See: http://de.selfhtml.org/css/eigenschaften/positionierung.htm#overflow
and in English: http://en.selfhtml.org/css/eigenschaften/positionierung.htm#overflow

Sample Snippet:

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Display display = new Display();
    Shell shell = new Shell(display);
    shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());

    Browser browser = new Browser(shell, SWT.NONE);
    browser.setText("<html><body style='overflow:auto;'>Hello World</body></html>");

    shell.open();
    while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
      if (!display.readAndDispatch()) {
        display.sleep();
      }
    }
  }
}

Ben


*** This bug has been marked as a duplicate of 86729 ***

